    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2224942,
      "reputation" : 1959,
      "user_id" : 1963930,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cea4ec28dad9b4cfbef823741b75340d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Craig Taylor",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1963930/craig-taylor"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 176,
    "last_activity_date" : 1568895959,
    "last_edit_date" : 1568895959,
    "creation_date" : 1504455548,
    "answer_id" : 46025437,
    "question_id" : 37972859,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Objects.isNull</code> is intended for use within Java 8 lambda filtering.  </p>\n\n<p>It's much easier and clearer to write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>.stream().filter(Objects::isNull) \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>than to write:</p>\n\n<pre><code>.stream().filter(x -&gt; x == null).  \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Within an <code>if</code> statement, however, either will work. The use of <code>== null</code> is probably easier to read but in the end it will boil down to a style preference. </p>\n"
  }, {
